\title{mnlfa: Moderated Nonlinear Factor Analysis}
\description{
The \strong{mnlfa} package implements the stepwise Moderated Nonlinear Factor
Analysis (MNLFA) procedure for assessing differential item functioning (DIF)
and measurement invariance in the presence of one or more observed moderator
variables.

Unlike existing R implementations, \strong{mnlfa} fully supports
\emph{multidimensional} measurement models with multiple correlated latent
variables (facets) per domain — the typical case when working with
hierarchical personality or ability constructs.
}
\section{Main workflow}{

A typical MNLFA analysis proceeds in six steps:
\enumerate{
\item \strong{Baseline CFAs}: fit one CFA per facet with
\code{\link[=run_mxsem]{run_mxsem()}} (\code{scale_latent_variances = TRUE}).
\item \strong{Screen latent mean moderation}: call
\code{\link[=add_latent_mean_regression]{add_latent_mean_regression()}} + \code{\link[=run_mxsem]{run_mxsem()}} +
\code{\link[=significant_mean_moderators]{significant_mean_moderators()}} for each facet.
\item \strong{Screen item-level moderation}: call
\code{\link[=moderate_loadings_and_intercepts]{moderate_loadings_and_intercepts()}} + \code{\link[=run_mxsem]{run_mxsem()}} +
\code{\link[=significant_item_moderators]{significant_item_moderators()}} for each item within each facet.
\item \strong{Select anchor items}: rank items by Δ-SABIC; items with the
smallest improvement are best anchors.  At least two per facet are
required.
\item \strong{Build full domain model}: assemble the moderated syntax with
\code{\link[=build_full_domain_models]{build_full_domain_models()}} and re-fit with \code{\link[=run_mxsem]{run_mxsem()}}
(\verb{scale_loadings = FALSE, scale_latent_variances = FALSE}).
Optionally add covariance moderation (\code{\link[=add_covariance_moderation]{add_covariance_moderation()}})
and an acquiescence factor (\code{\link[=create_acquiescence_lines]{create_acquiescence_lines()}}).
\item \strong{Compute person-specific parameters}: use
\code{\link[=build_all_individual_parameters]{build_all_individual_parameters()}} to obtain individual factor loadings,
intercepts, latent means, and latent variances.
}
}

\section{Anchor item format}{

Anchor items are identified by the composite key \code{"facet_name.item_name"},
e.g. \code{"E_1.e1_i1"}.  This convention arises naturally from
\code{unlist(facet.items, recursive = FALSE)} in the pipeline.  The only
exception is \code{\link[=build_moderated_sem_one_latent]{build_moderated_sem_one_latent()}}, which uses bare item names.
}

\section{Data requirements and naming conventions}{


\strong{Data format.}  The data must be a \code{data.frame} in wide format with one
row per person.  All item columns and all moderator columns must be present.
Moderators should be numeric; binary variables (e.g. sex coded 0/1) are
supported.  Centring continuous moderators (e.g. z-standardisation) is
strongly recommended so that the log-variance intercept \verb{v0_*} and the
latent-mean intercept \verb{m_*} have a meaningful reference point.

\strong{Facet names.}  Latent variable names must follow the pattern
\verb{[LETTER]_[DIGIT(S)]}, e.g. \code{E_1}, \code{P_3}, \code{N_12}.  Several internal
regex patterns rely on this convention to extract domain names and parameter
labels.  The domain name is the part before the first underscore
(\code{sub("_.*", "", facet_name)}), so \code{P_1}, \code{P_2}, and \code{P_3} all belong to
domain \code{P} and will be assembled into a single domain model by
\code{\link[=build_full_domain_models]{build_full_domain_models()}}.

\strong{Item names.}  Item names must not contain dots (\code{.}), because the package
uses \code{.} as a separator in the composite anchor key \code{"facet.item"}.
Underscores are fine.  Item names must match exactly between the model
syntax string and the column names in the data frame.

\strong{Reversed items and the acquiescence factor.}  \code{\link[=create_acquiescence_lines]{create_acquiescence_lines()}}
assigns a loading of \code{+1} to regular items and \code{-1} to reversed items.
An item is treated as reversed if and only if its name contains the
substring \verb{_rec_} (case-sensitive), e.g. \code{e1_rec_i8}.  This substring must
appear in both the data column name and the model syntax string; the
simulation script demonstrates the required column renaming step:
\preformatted{
  names(data)[names(data) == "e1_i8"] <- "e1_rec_i8"
}

\strong{Fit indices.}  MNLFA models rely on definition variables (person-specific
parameters), which makes the standard reference model approach for computing
CFI, TLI, and RMSEA inapplicable.  All calls to \code{\link[=run_mxsem]{run_mxsem()}} in the
pipeline should therefore use \code{add_ref_models = FALSE}.  The sample-size
adjusted BIC (SABIC) is used instead for model comparison (Δ-SABIC for
anchor selection; SABIC for variance and mean moderation screening).
}

